{
    "name": "Protocol SubZero/443 (5v5/4v4)",
    "description": "Protocol SubZero/443 is a system that was found by the IDSS-443 (Interstellar Drone Survey Swarm). The IDSS-443 scanned the system and found SubZero/443-1 instance amongst other instances. Further analysis revealed significant planetary terraformation by [REDACTED]. IDSS-443 found storage disks orbiting SubZero/443-2. The drives contain information of civilization [REDACTED] and their attempts at terraforming their planet. In trying to heat up the planet [REDACTED] tried to drop [REDACTED] on two sides of the planet SubZero/443-1, but the protocol 443 failed due to miscalculation due to [REDACTED] not taking into account the majority of the planets core was frozen sponge like rock. When Protocol 443 was initiated, SubZero/433-2 was blown apart nearly in two. The remains of the planet, mainly instance SubZero/443-3 and instanec SubZero/443-4 orbit it to this day. The [REDACTED] tried to rebuild the planet SubZero/443-2 by using the remaining metal, but ultimately failed due to immense cold now even worse after the catastrophic protocol failure. The planet Subzero/443 core was blown off and the small amount of geotermal energy remaining quickly radiated into space.... SubZero/443-3 and SubZero/443-4 orbiting SubZero/443-2 did not help by blocking out the Subzero/443-1 (The star of the system, which is a very dim Red Dwarf Star) which was very far away as is. Amongst other creative protocol propositions, there was a protocol 444 as one of the propositions by the leader of [REDACTED] to [REDACTED] but it was failed due to being to expensive. Protocol 444 was to change the orbit of the planet by utilizing halleys (planetary engines). The foundation simulated the Protocol 444 and it would have been a success with only 2.32% failure rate but was 7433% more resource intensive than protocol 443 which had by their calculations 6.74% failure rate; but had they known the core of the SubZero/443 was mostly hollow they would have calculated a 99.61% failure rate.",
